titlestmt.titleproper: A Guide to the International Basic Economy Corporation (IBEC) records FA084

did.physdesc: This collection consists of: 107 record cartons, 52 document boxes, 1 flat box, 250 reels of microfilm, 2550 sheets of microfiche, photographs, and audio tapes.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The IBEC records are arranged in 14 series:
Series 5 - General Information - Data and Research

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The International Basic Economy Corporation (IBEC) (1947-1977) was founded by Nelson A. Rockefeller in January 1947. The Corporation was developed as a private business enterprise that would focus on upgrading the "basic economies" of lesser-developed nations by lowering food prices, building sound housing, mobilizing savings, and fostering industrialization. The objective was for the business to be profitable and sustainable, and to encourage others, especially nationals, to establish competitive businesses and thereby establish a "multiplier" development effect. In it's early years, 1947-1955, IBEC was especially focused in Latin America, specifically Brazil and Venezuela. The subsidiary Venezuelan Basic Economy Corporation (VBEC) was formed, which was divided into several companies: a fishing company, a food wholesaling company, which later became a retail supermarket company, and a milk company.

In Brazil, IBEC divided into five companies which provided specialized services to farmers. These companies individually focused in the areas of: hybrid seeds, hog experimentation, grain storage, helicopter crop-dusting, and mechanized agricultural services. IBEC also invested modestly in Brazilian manufacturing and investment banking.

During the period 1956-1971, IBEC's mission broadened to encompass new activities, such as mutual funds, housing, poultry, and soluble coffee companies. During this time IBEC expanded into other geographical areas, eventually having operations in thirty-three countries on four continents.

By 1972, the subsidiaries and joint ventures were reorganized into five operating groups: food, housing, distribution, industrial and financial services. The food group aimed at increasing the quality and yield of basic edible commodities in various host nations. The housing group concentrated on predominantly prefabricated low to medium-priced housing in the United States, Mexico, Peru, Puerto Rico and Brazil. The distribution group operated cash and carry supermarkets in several Latin American countries. The industrial group, including three U.S. subsidiaries, produced equipment for American industrial markets. The financial services group was instrumental in the development of indigenous capital markets in Brazil, Spain and Thailand.

In 1973, the company began a divestment program and by 1980, when IBEC merged with Booker McConnell Limited, was primarily engaged in agriculturally-related endeavors. In 1985 the company name was changed from IBEC, Inc. to Arbor Acres Farm, Inc.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Veronica Rossi minimally processed the paper records in 2002. Microforms were processed by Beth Jaffe-Davis.
The records remain in original folders and storage boxes.
Files are numbered consecutively in Series 1 through Series 8. Series 9 and 10 and Series 11 (Photographs) are each numbered separately.
File titles for the microforms include - Company name: Location or Department: File description.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The Rockefeller Archive Center has title, copyright, and literary rights in the collection, in so far as it holds them, and has authority to grant permission to cite and publish archival material from the collection.

appraisal.head: Appraisal
appraisal.p: It is believed that the original records filmed to microforms were destroyed following the filming. It is therefore likely that there is little to no overlap in content between paper records and microforms other than material which may have been maintained in more than one file location during active use of the documents.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The collection contains correspondence, memoranda, reports, publications, minutes, dockets, photographs, tape recordings, and films. The collection was created by the IBEC files department, and many documents contain department seals and marginal notes in pencil.

Subjects include agriculture in Latin America; the economics of agriculture; foreign business enterprise; economic development in Latin America; the food industry in Latin America, including egg production, fisheries, food crops, food distribution, and food production; housing; hybrid corn and hybrid seeds; investment banking and investment trusts; dried milk; poultry breeding; food preservation; coffee processing; swine breeding; silk manufacture and trade; and shopping centers and supermarkets in Latin America.
Among the companies represented in these files are: Arbor Acres Farm, Inc., Booker McConnell Limited, Cinva-Ram, and Venezuelan Basic Economy Corporation (VBEC).

Among the individuals who appear in the files are: Victor Andrade, Romulo Betancourt, David Dubinsky, John B. Griffing, Francis A. Jamieson, K. J. Kadow, Donald E. Meads, Robert Moses, Nelson A. Rockefeller, Rodman C. Rockefeller, and Winthrop Rockefeller.

Among the countries represented in this collection are: the Argentine Republic, Brazil, Bolivia, Chile, Colombia, Cuba, Ecuador, Latin America, Iran, Italy, Mexico, Peru, Puerto Rico, South America, Spain, Thailand, and Venezuela.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Archival Materials note
relatedmaterial.p: For related materials at RAC see:
FA079 American International Association for Economic and Social Development (AIA) records
FA339 Nelson A. Rockefeller personal papers, AIA-IBEC, Series B
Researchers may also wish to consult Wayne G. Broehl's book, "The International Basic Economy Corporation," which is available in the Rockefeller Archive Center Library.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition note
acqinfo.p: Rodman C. Rockefeller donated the IBEC records to the Rockefeller Archive Center in 1985.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The records in this series include information about projects and proposals that IBEC received from companies and government representatives from all over the world. There is some correspondence with important politicians in Latin America, such as the President of Chile, Eduardo Frei.

There are some lists of persons from IBEC who used the records. There are a lot of margin notes in pencil from the IBEC files department that describe the importance of the document; for example, in the folder titled "Japan-Industrialization", there is a label that says "for limited use only" with names of the people in IBEC who can read this information. Other marginal notes comment on facts about the operations, such as "this project did not materialize."
Most of the records are in English, but there are several documents in other languages, such as Portuguese, Spanish, French, Italian, German, Danish, and Greek, some with English translations.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: This series is arranged alphabetically, first by country, continent, or region, and thereunder by industry.

scopecontent.p: This series contains information regarding IBEC and its subsidiaries, such as Arbor Acres or Bellows-Valvair, and information regarding the internal organization of IBEC. The files include documents on finances; insurance; loans; legal fields, such as trademarks and mergers and acquisitions; board of directors meetings; stockholders meetings; general organization; staff; taxes; public relations; and publicity. Part of the series is in English but there are a lot of records in Spanish and some in Portuguese, French, Italian, and German.

scopecontent.p: Bernardo Jofre, Caracas, comments on Venezuela as a whole. 1964. Bernardo Jofre and Anthony Salva regarding Compania Anomina Distribuidora de Alimentos (CADA), Caracas, Venezuela. 1964. Field trip with Tony Salvar, visits to the supermarkets in Caracas, Venezuela. 1964. Rudolpho Mondolfi, early days of IBEC and the relation to Corporacion de Fomento, Caracas, Venezuela. 1964. Bernardo Jofre and Derek Nicholas concerning INSA, Caracas, Venezuela. 1964. Jim Moure comments on PESCA, Caracas, Venezuela. 1964. Gene Dye regarding IMLACA, ILAPECA, and DIBROLAC, Caracas, Venezuela. 1964. Field trip to Puerto la Cruz and to Margarita Island. 1964. Bill Coles comments on Hotel Avila, Caracas, Venezuela. 1964. arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The original order of the images is unknown, and the series has been arranged into six subseries based on subject and media:

Subseries 1 - Administration This subseries consists of four sections: Meetings, People, Reports, and Miscellaneous. The Meetings section is arranged alphabetically, and thereunder chronologically. The People section is arranged alphabetically, with materials of prominent IBEC personages such as Nelson A. Rockefeller and Rodman C. Rockefeller in separate folders. Reports are arranged alphabetically, then chronologically. The Miscellaneous section consists of one folder, "New York Office," which contains still images of the IBEC office space in New York City.

Subseries 2 - Nations and Industries This subseries consists of photographs organized alphabetically by country (or, in the case of "Africa," by continent). Under each country, the files are arranged alphabetically by the specific country (or acronym) in operation. Images that were not identified with a particular company or acronym have been placed in a "General" file for each country.

Subseries 3 - Photographs separated from IBEC records Prior to archival processing of the IBEC records, the records were reviewed and images were separated and placed in the IBEC Photograph series. This subseries consists of these images which are now housed in folders whose titles retain the original folder title from the IBEC records.
Subseries 4 - Slides This subseries consists of slides removed from subseries 1, 2, and 3. Within this series, the folder titles correspond with the original file from which the slides were removed.
Subseries 5 - Negatives This subseries consists of negatives removed from subseries 1, 2, and 3. A portion of the negatives were removed prior to archival processing of the collection, and therefore do not correspond exactly with the folder titles from earlier series; nevertheless, the majority of the negatives are arranged to correspond with the original file from which they were removed.
Subseries 6 - Duplicates and Extra Copies This subseries consists of duplicate images removed during processing and files originally labeled "Extra Copies." Between two to three copies of the same image were kept in the original file; any additional photographs were removed to this subseries.

For subseries 1, 2, and 3, all slides and negatives have been removed into subseries 4 and 5. The final box in this series (Box 53) contains oversized materials that have been removed from subseries 1, 2, and 3.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The IBEC Photograph Series primarily documents IBEC operations overseas, with the majority of the images from Latin American nations, most prominently Venezuela. While some of the images are labeled or possess captions, the majority of the images are unlabeled. The collection is varied, ranging from promotional photographs of prefabricated houses to panoramic views of the countryside to charts and graphs used in meetings or reports.

fileplan.head: File Plan
fileplan.p: This series is also referred to as Series 1052 of the RAC photographic holdings.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The Rockefeller Archive Center recognizes that our audiovisual materials may contain problematic language and/or content. The films, videos, and/or sound in this collection have not been altered in any way. All titles and/or content are illustrative of the creator's original vision. As such, this audiovisual collection may contain discriminatory visual and/or aural content that is representative of racial, gendered, or ableist biases.

Accompanying description, most often with creator or donor-generated language and terminology, has to this point been retained and maintained "as received" by RAC with minimal archivist intervention or augmentation.
We acknowledge these problems and aim to cultivate inclusive representation and equity by reconsidering and enhancing our description of this audiovisual material with current sensibilities.
